shared_text:
Brookville Lake, US Army Corps of Engineers, Louisville District
May 25 at 9:17 AM ·

You won't see this anywhere else...

We are currently putting the final touches on the annual "Dam Numbers" tradition which has been alive for over 30 years.

Usually, high school seniors volunteer to etch the numbers in by weedeater each year which loom over the town directly in sight from Franklin County High School. Covid 19 has hit Brookville pretty hard and we are unable to partner with the students so we are taking our own initiative to keep the tradition alive.

From all of us at The Corps of Engineers Brookville office we say KEEP TRUCKIN' class of 2020 and Happy Memorial day everyone!!

#corpslakes #brookvillelake #franklincountyindiana
-Ranger Beard

Sydney Graf‎Franklin County 2020 Seniors
May 16 at 4:59 PM ·

Attention FCHS seniors and parents:

This is the last call for cap and gown pictures for the senior class collage. I must have your photo no later than Tuesday, May 19th. NO exceptions. I understand that some may not have their cap and gown. If this is the case, then please submit just a senior photo of yourself. We would love for you to still be included in the photo, regardless of whether or not you have your cap and gown😊 I have only received about 60% of the class’s photos. Students have been reminded a couple of times over the past months via email and details have also been released on social media about this project. I am having the college arranged professionally, so I must have all of the photos collected no later than May 19th. If you have questions about the picture please feel free to message me.

You can either send me the photos via social media or you may send them to my school email! Your students will have access to this email address! Thank you so much!

post_text:
FCHS Spring Sports Parents-- we know you are greatly saddened by the cancelation of your child's spring sports season. We are, too. We would like to acknowledge this great group of hardworking individuals in their high school yearbook. If you have a picture of your child playing their spring sport from years past and would like it to appear in the yearbook this year, please email the photo in jpeg format to Mrs. Hudepohl -- lhudepohl@fccsc.k12.in.us.

Also, anyone who still needs to order this year's yearbook can go to walsworthyearbooks.com. Select the "buy a yearbook" link at the top of the page and enter the school's information.

Damaged Chromebooks can be brought to Franklin County HS for repair on Tuesdays and Thursdays from 2-5pm. If you have a child in grades 3, 4, or 5 and you need a Chromebook, you can also pickup a loaner at FCHS. When you arrive, please call the high school (765-647-4101) and a technician will greet you at the door.

This service is offered on Tuesdays and Thursdays from 2-5 pm.

post_text: Did you know that April 1, 2020 is Census Day? Responding to the #2020Census is our civic duty and affects the amount of funding for our community’s public resources. Counting your child in the 2020 census could mean $10,000 of additional funding for K12 schools over the next ten years. To learn more, visit http://www.census.indiana.edu/

Cassie Garrett
March 24 at 10:55 PM ·

Yesterday, kind of last minute I thought how nice it would be if I could get a teacher or two to write a little note for the kiddos at school. So yesterday evening I put a post on my personal Facebook page and thought I would hopefully fill the few spots I had empty by morning.

Pretty soon it was apparent the kid's page this week was going to be dedicated to the teachers. I took my last one two hours before deadline and it just so happens there was room for only one thing, the eLearning schedule! 😊

What a great community!!

Community Mental Health Center has extended a helping hand and will provide services to students, parents and staff that need help. This includes phone call sessions, crisis supports and assessments. They can provide all services over the phone to assist with your needs during these difficult times.

If you or a family member would like to talk to a therapist, you can contact the local office and be set up with a therapist for phone sessions.

Please know there are people out there that can help you through this. It’s okay to be scared. It’s okay to have anxiety. We are all in this together!

Community Mental Health Center: 765-647-4173.

Franklin County Indiana Sheriff's Department
March 3 at 10:10 AM ·

Deputy Andrew Voelker completes 2nd full month as new Franklin County School Resource Officer.

Beginning with the 2020 budget, the Franklin County Community School Corporation and Franklin County Sheriff's Department have partnered again with addition of a 2nd School Resource Officer. Deputy Voelker is a 2007 graduate of Franklin County High School, a United States Marine veteran, and a graduate of the 209th session of the Indiana Law Enforcement Academy. Deputy Voelker has joined Deputy Jason Lovins in this capacity and is excited about his transition to the school.

Purdue Fast Start Program - Undergraduate Admissions - Purdue University

Franklin County Indiana 4-H Fair
February 19 at 10:54 AM ·

On Tuesday, February 18th Purdue University announced the launch of the Purdue Fast Start program, an opportunity for Indiana high school students to earn up to a year of free college credit from Purdue University. Purdue Extension has partnered with the office of admissions to spread the word about this initiative that furthers Purdue’s land-grant mission and aims to make higher education more affordable and accessible for all. Here are the basics:
• Students who pass a minimum of five College Level Examination Program (CLEP) exams will be assured admission to Purdue University.
• Modern States (the online learning platform for advanced-placement courses) provides more than 30 free online courses to help students prepare for CLEP exams.
• A $1 million gift from the founder and CEO of Modern States, Steve Klinsky, and his wife Maureen will cover the cost of 10,000 CLEP exam fees for Indiana students.
• You can learn more by visiting purdue.university/faststart, or calling 765-494-1776 (800-743-3333 for hearing impaired).
